Just to expand on this topic...

Source code is a *wonderful* resource to h=
ave when attempting to apply
technology described in a research paper, part=
icularly for the family of
NEAT algorithms where the solution is complex an=
d heavily parameterized.

However, in addition to Ken&#39;s points, it&#39;s also w=
orth pointing out that
there are times when companies and indeed private in=
dividuals may be in the
process of commercializing their research, and requ=
iring code submission is
a disincentive for sharing their discoveries with =
the world (other than in
their commercialized, black box form).  There are =
times where the benefit
of publication in terms of notoriety, and indeed th=
e altruistic goal of
simply broadening humanity&#39;s knowledge, are worth shar=
ing insights and
experimental results, but NOT worth providing a software p=
ackage that could
be easily downloaded and used to start a rival product.

